To many people around the world, “hula” may conjure images of plastic
dancers shaking their hips on car dashboards. But long before hula was
commodified,itwasasacred danceamong NativeHawaiians– an ancient
practice that served as an archive of their stories, beliefs and way of life.
There was no written language in ancient Hawai''i. Instead, the Hawaiians
used oral tradition and hula to pass on their identity and culture from one
generation to thenext.
